<section xml:id="C28.S19">
<title>Expansions in Series of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S19.m1">\mathrm{me}_{\nu+2n}</Math> Functions</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C28.S19.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.s1">
Let <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.m1">q</Math> be a normal value (ยง28.12(i)) with respect to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.m2">\nu</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.m3">f(z)</Math> be a function that is analytic on a doubly-infinite open strip <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.m4">S</Math> that contains the real axis.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.s2">
Assume also <Math equation-number="28.19.1" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S19.E1">f(z+\pi)=e^{\mathrm{i}\nu\pi}f(z)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.s3">
Then <Math equation-number="28.19.2" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S19.E2">f(z)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}f_{n}\mathrm{me}_{\nu+2n}\left(z,q\right),</Math> where <Math equation-number="28.19.3" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S19.E3">f_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\pi}f(z)\mathrm{me}_{\nu+2n}\left(-z,q\right) \mathrm{d}z</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.s4">
The series (28.19.2) converges absolutely and uniformly on compact subsets within <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S19.p1.m5">S</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C28.S19.Px1">
<title>Example</title>   
<para xml:id="C28.S19.Px1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C28.S19.Px1.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="28.19.4" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S19.E4">e^{\mathrm{i}\nu z}=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}c^{\nu+2n}_{-2n}(q)\mathrm{me}_{ \nu+2n}\left(z,q\right),</Math> where the coefficients are as in ยง28.14.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
</section>
